John Edward: Linguistic competences are fundamental for the citizens of the world
The independent educational centres in Scotland have a history of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another set of outstanding results in the exams that are reinforced by individual and collective successes in the fields of sport, art, music and other community projects.
With more than 30 000 students throughout Scotland, these centres, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Colleges (SCIS, for their English acronyms), strive to deliver the best level of service to students and parents.
Independent colleges aim to prepare their students to continue their higher education studies, for the career they choose and for the place they occupy as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement an adapted curriculum, it is observed that modern languages remain a popular and desired subject in the centres.
As Nelson Mandela said: \"If you speak to a man in a language he understands, the message reaches his head.
If you speak to him in his tongue, he reaches his heart.
This is a powerful reminder that if you want to establish relationships and build trust with people from other countries, you cannot rely solely on English.
If we take into account the recent results of this year's exams, we can observe that languages are at the top of the classification tables, being the highest approval rates in independent schools.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages obtained an A, the highest grade.
The data, collected from the 74 SCIS centres, showed that 72% of students obtained an A in Mandarin, 72% of those studying in German, 69% of those studying in French and 63% of those studying in Spanish also obtained an A.
This shows that the independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages by considering them as a fundamental competence that both children and young people will need in the future without doubt.
Currently, it is considered that, as a subject, languages are at the same level as the CTIM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the study plans of independent colleges and everywhere.
A survey carried out in 2014 by the United Kingdom's Employment and Skills Commission revealed that 17 % of employers' reasons for the difficulties they faced in filling jobs were attributed to the lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly indispensable in preparing young people for their future careers.
The potential job opportunities that require languages are increasing, so these competencies are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career that someone chooses, if he has learned a second language, he will have a real advantage in the future thanks to a competition like this, which will last a lifetime.
Being able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will allow such a person to automatically advance to competition.
According to a survey conducted by YouGov among more than 4000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% of them did not speak any foreign language well enough to maintain a conversation, and it was also established that the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, 15%, was French.
For this reason, investing in language education is now important for children today.
If they know several languages, especially those of developing economies, children will be equipped to have better opportunities to find quality jobs.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some centres will focus on the most classic modern languages, while others will teach languages considered most important for the United Kingdom by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of a child, independent colleges can always choose from a number of languages provided by specialized teaching staff in this area.
Scotland's independent educational centres devote all their efforts to providing a learning environment that prepares children and that teams with the necessary skills to succeed, whatever the future holds for them.
At present, it is undeniable that, in a global business environment, languages remain vital to the future of the country, and this should therefore be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should be regarded as “competences for international communication”
Independent colleges will continue to offer these options, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
You have to do it.
