The National Trust is spying on the secret life of bats
This new research, which has been carried out in a state of the Scottish Highlands, tries to discover how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
Everything we find is expected to shed more light on the behavior of the only flying mammals and help guide the next conservation activities.
The study, carried out by the National Trust for Scotland, will follow the common and soprano bats, as well as the coastal bats of Daubenton and long ear browns of the Inverewe gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in strategic locations of the property to track the activities of bats during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also carry out mobile research with portable detectors.
Experts will analyze the sounds collected in the recordings to discover the frequency of calls from bats and what species do.
A report and a map of the habitat will then be produced to create a detailed picture of the environment and its behaviour.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation consultant for NTS, hopes that the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as the creation of grasslands and how forests should be maintained for bats and other associated species.
The bat populations in Scotland and the United Kingdom have been considerably reduced in the last century.
They are under threat from the construction and development that affects their nests and the loss of their habitat.
Wind turbines and electrical wiring can also pose a risk to them, as can insecticide papers and other chemical treatments of building materials or domestic cat attacks.
The bats aren't really blind,
but, because of their night hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes to achieve their goal.
They use a sophisticated eco-location technique that locates ants and obstacles in their flight route.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76 000 hectares of land throughout the country, takes the subject of the bats very seriously.
He has ten trained experts on the subject, who regularly conduct surveys, nest inspections and, at times, rescues.
The organization has inaugurated even the first and only reservation dedicated to bats of Scotland in the state of Treave in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of the ten species of bats of Scotland.
The director of the property, David Thompson, says it is the ideal territory for them.
“Here, in Three, we have a fantastic area for bats,” he said.
We have old buildings, many old trees and all the right habitat.
However, there are still many unknown things about bats, so the work we do here and in other properties will help us better understand what they need to develop.
It emphasizes the importance of checking whether there are bats before carrying out maintenance tasks within the properties, since a breeding colony can be unintentionally destroyed and 400 females and offspring could be killed, which would mean the annihilation of a local population.
The bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, harass or disturb them, as well as destroy their colonies.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish officer in charge of the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to cooperate.
He said, \"We still have a lot to learn about bats and many other species we don't know how their populations evolve.\"
