Update of the red tide: Decrease concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The new Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission report (Fishing and Wildlife Commission in Florida) shows a general reduction in red tide concentrations in areas of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, irregular flowering conditions are being reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a reduction in concentrations.
The flowering of the red tide extends approximately along 130 miles of coastline from the county of Pinellas to the north to the county of Lee to the south.
Irregular plots can be found about 10 miles from Hillsborough County coast, but in fewer places if compared to last week.
Red tide has also been detected in Pasco County.
During the past week, average concentrations have been reported in Pinellas County and its coast, low-to-high concentrations on the Hillsborough County coast, high-to-high bottom concentrations in Manatee County, high-to-bottom concentrations in Sarasota County and its coast, medium-to-middle concentrations in Charlotte County, high-to-high bottom concentrations in Lee County and its coast, and low concentrations in Collier County.
Respiratory irritation problems continue to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory irritation problems have been reported in the northwest area of Florida during the past week.
